" lang="en">National/Public Security</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gsec"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gvexe"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Executive Branch</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvdhs"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/FDL G/IGV N/ELX N/GEN N/PLT R/ASI R/EEU R/EU R/FEO R/NME R/RS R/UR R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday PTC BALLOTS ELECTION MEDDLING ELECTIONS FEDERAL GOVERNMENT NATIONAL SECURITY RUSSIA PROBE SB120131101041198133275045841155521407205221 Clinton, Hillary Donald Trump Johnson, Jeh Nielsen, Kirstjen SYND CODES_REVIEWED Politics and Policy </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OPOL </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Politics</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Homeland Security Chief Says U.S. Is Improving Election Defenses; Kirstjen Nielsen tells Congress that information-sharing is getting better, but limits remain on federal efforts since state and local cooperation is voluntary</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>WASHINGTON—The U.S. has made significant strides in better protecting the election system after a Russian campaign of hacking and misinformation during the 2016 election, the Trump administration's Homeland Security chief told Congress on Wednesday.</Para><Para>Kirstjen Nielsen, the secretary of Homeland Security, testified to the Senate Intelligence Committee that information sharing between the federal government and states and localities had improved since the last election. State and local officials, she said, are getting more access to classified information and better support from the federal government in protecting their voting systems.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"Today I can say with confidence that we know whom to contact in every state to share threat information" Ms. Nielsen told the panel—a capability she said didn't exist in 2016.</Para><Para>Ms. Nielsen also said that 20 state election officials had been granted security clearances to give them access to such information, and that the Department would immediately brief any state or local official on threats against their systems, even if the information was classified and even if the official lacked a clearance.</Para><Para>But she also stressed that there are limits on what the federal government can do, given that elections remain the responsibility of state, county, local and municipal governments—and that cooperation with Washington by those governments was voluntary.</Para><Para>Ms. Nielsen's testimony was part of a yearlong investigation by the Senate Intelligence Committee into Russian activity during the 2016 election.</Para><Para>Lawmakers of both parties have expressed concern about the integrity of this fall's congressional elections. Ms. Nielsen and other top officials continue to stress that the <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midterm-elections-remain-vulnerable-to-russian-meddling-u-s-spy-chief-says-1518539348">U.S. election system is still vulnerable </ELink>to foreign interference—particularly disinformation, foreign propaganda and cyberattacks against voting systems.</Para><Para>U.S. intelligence agencies have said the Kremlin sanctioned a campaign of hacking, leaking and disinformation aimed at boosting President Donald Trump over his Democratic rival, Hillary Clinton, and sowing discord in U.S. domestic politics. Mr. Trump has repeatedly said that his campaign had nothing to do with any Russian election interference, and Russia has denied any effort to influence the outcome.</Para><Para>Mr. Trump has shown little public interest in the topic of election security, and has said Democrats' complaints about possible Russian influence were an excuse for losing the election. But Ms. Nielsen said that top Trump administration national security officials held a recent meeting to address how to protect the 2018 election.</Para><Para>Sen. Mark Warner, the top Democrat on the panel, criticized the administration's handling of the issue.</Para><Para>"The threat is real, the need to act is urgent. We need the administration to accelerate its efforts," the Virginia senator said. "Perhaps most of all, we need a president who will acknowledge the gravity of this threat."</Para><Para>This week, Congress is expected to consider new election security measures as part of <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/congressional-leaders-race-to-finalize-spending-deal-1521641432">a must-pass spending bill</ELink>. Bipartisan negotiators are expected to include $380 million in grants to state and local governments to help improve election security, as well as additional money for law enforcement to help.</Para><Para>The last time Congress made a significant pool of money available for election infrastructure upgrades was after the disputed 2000 election, when it offered more than $3 billion to state and local governments.</Para><Para>The Senate Intelligence Committee also <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-panel-urges-election-security-in-report-on-russian-interference-1521564622">released recommendations this week</ELink> to states, urging them to move to more paper ballots or electronic systems with paper backups. A number of states still rely on digital voting machines with no paper backup—a technology that Ms. Nielsen acknowledged was a concern.</Para><Para>"If there's no way to audit the election, that is absolutely a national security concern," she said.</Para><Para>Ms. Nielsen appeared alongside former DHS secretary Jeh Johnson, who presided over the federal government's response to the Russian campaign during the 2016 election. The Obama administration's response also came under criticism from lawmakers of both parties during the hearing.</Para><Para>Mr. Johnson said the Obama administration had tried to warn the public about the continuing Russian effort, but that their message was drowned out by other events such as the fast-moving 2016 presidential campaign.</Para><Para>"We were beating the drum pretty hard," Mr. Johnson said.</Para><Para>Write to Byron Tau at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:byron.tau@wsj.com">byron.tau@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Byron Tau </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/homeland-security-chief-says-u-s-is-improving-election-defenses-1521651927" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

